{"sequence":39,"timestamp":"2026-04-10T07:00:43.056818079Z","event_type":"amendment_queued","details":{"amendment_id":"fr-2-85624bb1","body":"Teach resume to recover a run that dies after `run.json` is written but before `run_started` reaches the journal. The start path exposes a `Running` snapshot before `run_started` is durable (`src/contexts/workflow_composition/engine.rs:1095-1106`). If the orchestrator is killed in that window, stale-run reconciliation turns the snapshot into `Failed`, but resume still hard-requires a `run_started` entry in both `stage_plan_for_resume` and `derive_resume_state` (`src/contexts/workflow_composition/engine.rs:6455-6464` and `src/contexts/workflow_composition/engine.rs:6489-6498`). The result is that `run resume` still aborts with \"run journal does not contain a run_started event\" for one of the core process-death windows. Add a fallback that reconstructs the resume state from `interrupted_run`/`active_run`, or make startup journal durability happen before the `Running` snapshot is published.","dedup_key":"e2964f3961ff249ac6138dbe8c0e2c529e07bfc83178f450196556e7140b9fde","reviewer_sources":[{"backend_family":"codex","model_id":"gpt-5.4-xhigh","reviewer_id":"reviewer-1"}],"run_id":"run-20260410054251","source":"workflow_stage","source_stage":"final_review"}}
{"sequence":40,"timestamp":"2026-04-10T07:00:43.066088272Z","event_type":"amendment_queued","details":{"amendment_id":"fr-2-a4b2ef72","body":"Stop deleting `run.pid` just because the snapshot is not yet `Running`. `run stop` currently removes the pid file in the non-running fast path (`src/cli/run.rs:1911-1914`), while both start and resume now write `run.pid` before they persist the `Running` snapshot (`src/contexts/workflow_composition/engine.rs:1090-1098` and `src/contexts/workflow_composition/engine.rs:1809-1815`). A concurrent `run stop` in that startup window will return \"not currently running\" but still delete the live orchestrator's pid record, after which `run status`/`run resume` misclassify the still-running process as stale. Only clear `run.pid` after you have proven the recorded process is dead, or coordinate `run stop` with startup via the writer lease.","dedup_key":"200701b76ca0610a5bfe2ab03a4346501233da14576cef64733279c9af358c22","reviewer_sources":[{"backend_family":"codex","model_id":"gpt-5.4-xhigh","reviewer_id":"reviewer-1"}],"run_id":"run-20260410054251","source":"workflow_stage","source_stage":"final_review"}}
{"sequence":41,"timestamp":"2026-04-10T07:00:43.075187814Z","event_type":"amendment_queued","details":{"amendment_id":"fr-2-35bafcb9","body":"Make `run stop` verify that the SIGKILL path actually terminated the process before it rewrites state and reclaims locks. After the SIGTERM grace period, the code sends SIGKILL and discards the result of the follow-up liveness wait (`src/cli/run.rs:1962-1964`), then immediately reclaims the writer lease and may mark the snapshot failed as if the run were stopped (`src/cli/run.rs:1967-1986`). On Unix a successful `kill(SIGKILL)` does not guarantee the process is gone immediately, especially if it is stuck in uninterruptible I/O, so this can split-brain the project by releasing the lock and rewriting `run.json` while the orchestrator is still alive. If the post-SIGKILL liveness check still says the pid is alive, `run stop` should fail and leave recovery state untouched.","dedup_key":"325d8b522ca6c072b29d502e9dc2699f7ca521bf26e81f1dca055506440200d9","reviewer_sources":[{"backend_family":"codex","model_id":"gpt-5.4-xhigh","reviewer_id":"reviewer-1"}],"run_id":"run-20260410054251","source":"workflow_stage","source_stage":"final_review"}}
{"sequence":42,"timestamp":"2026-04-10T07:00:43.084281395Z","event_type":"amendment_queued","details":{"amendment_id":"fr-2-119ee7f5","body":"`src/contexts/workflow_composition/engine.rs:5649-5664` converts a resumable completion blocker into a failed snapshot path (`snapshot.status = RunStatus::Failed; snapshot.active_run = None;`), writes it, then returns early without calling `FileSystem::remove_pid_file`. This leaves `run.pid` behind after a terminal non-running outcome. Same function therefore violates PID cleanup in a normal terminal failure mode (`complete_guard`), which should always delete the orchestrator liveness file.","dedup_key":"a7a7fd551e1fca06a78f746a855f13a678f015f2163fb32f26189800e25ecbc2","reviewer_sources":[{"backend_family":"codex","model_id":"gpt-5.3-codex-spark-xhigh","reviewer_id":"reviewer-2"}],"run_id":"run-20260410054251","source":"workflow_stage","source_stage":"final_review"}}
{"sequence":43,"timestamp":"2026-04-10T07:00:43.093447201Z","event_type":"amendment_queued","details":{"amendment_id":"fr-2-fa266dd6","body":"`src/contexts/workflow_composition/engine.rs:5667-5684` in `complete_run` writes a completed snapshot first, then appends `run_completed` with `?`; if that append fails, the function returns before reaching `remove_pid_file`, and the PID file is never removed. If the snapshot write succeeds, the run is marked `Completed` in durable state while the completion event is absent and the PID liveness file remains.","dedup_key":"1195d35202229c0091d5f676466623b2d095371a473b30dbb58567b273d93670","reviewer_sources":[{"backend_family":"codex","model_id":"gpt-5.3-codex-spark-xhigh","reviewer_id":"reviewer-2"}],"run_id":"run-20260410054251","source":"workflow_stage","source_stage":"final_review"}}
